Can you add more here? You are trying to make clang-16 work with the locks? 99.9% of the time (this included), 5 words is not enough of a commit msg. :) 

Looks like you removed the 
    BMCWEB_LOG_ERROR
        << "This code is disabled due to clang-tidy issues that prevent CI "
           "from passing.";
    std::terminate();

Can you add a link to
https://github.com/openbmc/bmcweb/commit/26b3630b181d1093483e4d5ebe6aeeb91a6a2976 
explaining why this was added (e.g. to move to clang-16, std::terminate was added). 

I thought there were plans to move this to D-Bus, I am fine with this commit but can you please comment on future plans?

updated commit message as suggested.
we are still discussing on future plans, will update you
Done
How did you test?
updated tested by section
Done
This is technically relying on undefined overflow behavior still.

I see static_cast used in multiple other places in bmcweb.
what do you suggest here?

static_cast isn't the problem, it's static_cast<uint8_t>(uint64_t).  I don't think you'll find that anywhere else in bmcweb code.

Considering that this data structure is not passed on the wire anywhere, I would recommend representing it as std::array<uint8_t, 8> everywhere, instead of uint64_t, then you can easily index in, loop, and do whatever you need to.
PS, if there is somehwhere that you've seen bmcweb code doing static_cast<uint8_t>(uint64_t), please point it out so that we can either verify it's correct, or get it fixed.

actually user input resourceId as unit64, converting uint64 to std::array<uint8_t, 8> is causing clang-tidy-16 errors.
I wil try to use std::array<uint8_t, 8>
modified to use std::array<uint8_t, 8>
are we good with the change? Can you please check
Why is this required?  can't we just compare against 0?
Ah, sorry, read this as 0, not 8.  Please just inline this.
suggesting to use 'inline' for this variable ?
Just declare it where it's used.
Done
This is no more safe than the reinterpret cast before, and is using banned functions (ie memcpy).
got it, removed memcpy
Done

Probably what you want here is

qPosition = 0xFF && (resourceId1 >> (8 * position));
yes this works
pPosition =  static_cast<uint8_t>( 0xFF && (resourceId1 >> (8 * position)));
Not this patchset, but can we get rid of all these boost::equals?  They really shouldn't be required.
ok, will

boost::equals used in multiple places in this file
will try to put a separate commit to fix these
Done
Given that this function is now operating bytewise, I don't think an endian swap is neccesary?
it is not necessary, but we are following big endian notations in this code while processing lock record sections which is easily understandable.
Please remove.  There's no need to do endian conversion if we're operating on this as a series of bytes.
Doesn't look done, but it's not worth arguing about.  Thanks for making the other changes.
this involves more changes & byte order notations will change if we remove this big endian conversion. locks records have sections which we process which is readable & easy in big endian notations
Thank you so much for quick reviews on this commit

Can this just be sizeof(resourceId1)

?

this can now never be false, because of the check on line 520.
